---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import ContactEmail from '../components/ContactEmail.astro';
---

<PageLayout
  title="About Ramen Guide: Coverage & Method"
  description="What Ramen Guide covers, how it researches Japanese ramen styles and regional bowls, who writes it, and the principles behind every post."
>
  <p>
    <strong>Ramen Guide</strong> is an independent publication about Japanese ramen: what defines
    each style, where the regional bowls come from, and how a great bowl is actually built, from
    tare to noodles to toppings.
  </p>

  <h2>What we cover</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Ramen styles:</strong> shoyu, shio, miso, tonkotsu, tsukemen, mazesoba, and the rest —
      what defines each, how they differ, and how to recognize them in the wild.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Regional ramen:</strong> Japan's local bowls, from Sapporo miso to Hakata tonkotsu to
      Kitakata shoyu, and the histories and shops behind them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ingredients and technique:</strong> broths, tare, aroma oils, noodle hydration,
      chashu, ajitama, and the craft that separates a good bowl from a great one.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Where to eat:</strong> notable shops, ordering etiquette, and how to navigate a
      ticket-machine counter like a regular.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who writes it</h2>
  <p>
    Ramen Guide is published by a small editorial team under the Ramen Guide brand rather than under
    individual bylines. We care about the durability of the information, not the personality behind
    it. Every post is researched, sourced, and reviewed against our
    <a href="/editorial-standards/">editorial standards</a>, and we disclose how and where AI tools
    are used in our process.
  </p>

  <h2>How we fund the work</h2>
  <p>
    The publication is reader-focused and intends to support its work through display advertising and
    occasional affiliate relationships. Advertising never influences editorial judgement, and any
    affiliate relationship that affects a recommendation is disclosed inline. See our
    <a href="/disclaimer/">disclaimer and disclosures</a> for the full policy.
  </p>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>
  <p>
    Corrections, questions, and tips are welcome at
    <ContactEmail />, or via our
    <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>. You can also follow new posts over
    <a href="/rss.xml">RSS</a>.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
